I am a young and driven entrepeneur. It was on a holiday, when visiting relatives in Bali (Indonesia), that I came into contact with the Kopi Luwak Industry. This means that the kopi luwak war amongst the farmers of Indonesia must end and business must see to re-establishing the purity of the product. In this way the value of the Kopi Luwak, as far as the price is concerned, will also increase, so that part of the income could be used to invest - supported by Unicef - in healthcare and education.
Nowadays the management of the Kopi Luwak Industry, as far as the supply chain is concerned, has changed considerably by the integration of high tech equipment with the aim of enhancing the quality of the product.
Furthermore3 the tackling of unfair business, that is to sell impure Kopi Luwak, may have an impact on the state of mind of the children growing up in the Republic of Indonesia, for then they see that standard business should  be based on fair principles. I wonder, I wonder, what you would do if you had the power to dream at night any dream you wanted to dream? And you would, of course, be able to alter your time sense, and slip, say, 75 years of subjective time into 8 hours of sleep.

You would, I suppose, start out by fulfilling all your wishes. You could design for yourself what would be the most ecstatic life: love affairs, banquets, dancing girls, wonderful journeys, gardens, music beyond belief.

And then, after a couple of months of this sort of thing, at 75 years a night, you'd be getting a little taste for something different, and you would move over to an adventurous dimension, where there was sudden dangers involved, and the thrill of dealing with dangers. And you could rescue princesses from dragons, and go on dangerous journeys, make wonderful explosions and blow them up, eventually get into contest with enemies.

And after you'd done that for some time, you'd think up a new wrinkle: to forget that you were dreaming, so that you would think it was all for real, and to be anxious about it. Because it'd be so great when you woke up.

And then you'd say, well, like children who dare each other on things, how far out could you get? What could you take? What dimension of being lost, of abandonment of your power - what dimension of that could you stand? You could ask yourself this 'cause you know you'd eventually wake up.

And after you'd gone on doing this, you see, for some time, you'd suddenly find yourself sitting around in this room, with all your personal involvements, problems, etc... talking with me.

How do you know that that's not what you're doing? Could be, because after all, what would you do if you were god? Because if you were, well, there is, the Self. In the Upanishads, the basic texts of Hinduism, one of them starts out saying, "In the beginning was the Self, and looking around, it said, 'I am.'" And thus it is that everyone to this day, when asked, "Who is there?" says, "It is I."

If you were god, and in this sense that you knew everything, you would be bored. Because, if looking at it from another way, we pushed technology to its furthest possible development, and we had, instead of a dial telephone on one's desk, a more complex system of buttons, and one touch would give you anything you wanted; Aladdin's lamp. You would eventually have to introduce a button, labeled, "Surprise." Because all perfectly known futures, as I pointed out, are past; they have happened, virtually. It is only the true future is a surprise.

- Alan Watts

I know Hammond and May think my 928 Porsche is a bit dull, but for one very good reason, it isn't dull to me. You see, back in 1994, I was living in London, I got a call one evening from my mum to say that my dad was desperately ill in a hospital in Sheffield, and I needed to get there as quickly as possible.

I'd just taken the chicken out of the oven, and I thought, well, I'll take that for my mum because she won't have eaten, ran outside, and I had a 928 on test that week.

And when I arrived in Sheffield, the chicken was still warm, and my dad was still alive; in fact, he died half an hour later.

And the truth is, if I hadn't have been driving a car which could sit quite happily at 170 miles an hour, I wouldn't have had the opportunity to say goodbye to my dad.

So as far as I'm concerned, the 928 is alright.

- Jeremy Clarkson

You remember Archimedes of Syracuse, eh? The king asks Archimedes to determine if a present he's received is actually solid gold. Unsolved problem at the time.

It tortures the great Greek mathematician for weeks. Insomnia haunts him and he twists and turns in his bed for nights on end.

Finally, his equally exhausted wife... she's forced to share a bed with this genius... convinces him to take a bath to relax.

While he's entering the tub, Archimedes notices the bath water rise. Displacement, a way to determine volume, and that's a way to determine density... weight over volume.

And thus, Archimedes solves the problem. He screams "Eureka!" and he is so overwhelmed he runs dripping naked through the streets to the king's palace to report his discovery.

Now, what is the moral of the story?

~ Maximillian Cohen ~

That a breakthrough will come.

~ Sol Robeson ~

Wrong! The point of the story is the wife. You listen to your wife, she will give you perspective. Meaning, you need a break, you have to take a bath or you will get nowhere. There will be no order, only chaos.

Alston Alvin (Harrogate, United Kingdom) makes films, photos and media art. With the use of appropriated materials which are borrowed from a day-to-day context, Alvin creates work in which a fascination with the clarity of content and an uncompromising attitude towards conceptual and minimal art can be found. The work is aloof and systematic and a cool and neutral imagery is used.

His films never shows the complete structure. This results in the fact that the artist can easily imagine an own interpretation without being hindered by the historical reality. By examining the ambiguity and origination via retakes and variations, he tries to increase the dynamic between audience and author by objectifying emotions and investigating the duality that develops through different interpretations.

His practice provides a useful set of allegorical tools for manoeuvring with a pseudo-minimalist approach in the world of film: these meticulously planned works resound and resonate with images culled from the fantastical realm of imagination. By manipulating the viewer to create confusion, he often creates several practically identical works, upon which thoughts that have apparently just been developed are manifested: notes are made and then crossed out again, ‘mistakes’ are repeated.\nhttp://contacttelephonenumbers.com/

https://mirage.io (current) -- MirageOS is the 'M' in the MISO stack. A new approach to the Operating System where developers compose their applications by pulling in OS components as libraries (e.g networking, etc) and let the compiler deal with optimisation to produce lean, single-purpose VMs (aka Unikernels). Algorithms designed to solve mathematical problems were the reason I got involved in Computer Science as a freshman studying Mathematics and Mechanical Engineering five years ago; ever since, these have been the problems that have defined my professional and academic pursuits. The breadth and multidisciplinary nature of my subsequent experiences has given rise to many different applications (computational geometry and meshing, computational neuroscience, and computational mechanics/acoustics) in many different environments (internships at large simulation companies, appointments at university research groups, and a full time R&D position at US defense contractor). These experiences, however, have all been related by the common theme of combining Computer Science and rigorous mathematics to solve exciting computational problems. Now, holding a B.Sc. in Computer Science and Mechanical Engineering, I seek to extend this lineage of computational software development into the field of statistical learning (Machine Learning, Artificial Intelligence, et al) with a Master’s degree in Computer Science from Brown University; and though I have limited formal experience in this specific concentrations of Computer Science, the breadth and intensity of my general mathematical and computational preparation is evident – skills which are fundamentally requisite and correlated to success in the field of machine learning. Early in my undergraduate career, I began exerting substantial effort to the pursuit of computational and mathematical endeavors well beyond the requirement of my major, taking rigorous coursework in theoretic mathematics, simulation, and algorithms. The result of this was a high level of mathematical exposure, theoretical maturity, and perspective regarding the applications of my academic interests. This summarizes my experience at the University of North Dakota, and culminated in a year-long full-time appointment at the Pittsburgh-based simulation company ANSYS. This experience further refined and solidified my interests in mathematical applications in Computer Science, and inspired the last-minute addition of a major in Computer Science upon transferring to the University of Pittsburgh. These experiences had intensely refined my academic interests, and my time in Pittsburgh was spent working in computational and research capacities for 20-30 hours a week, in addition the coursework required to complete my two technical majors without delaying graduation. Assuredly, my GPA could have been improved by not perusing these time consuming endeavors, but I knew my interests and my priorities (for better or worse) were shifted accordingly.

What is blogHeard?

blogHeard is a youTube video publication company providing automatic video conversions for image and text bloggers. Users give us a link to their blog and we create a youTube video from their blog and email them a link to the youTube version of their blog. An example of image bloggers are the Pin bloggers on Pinterest.com. An example of text bloggers (which usually include some images) are the bloggers on blogspot.com.

Our technology: You can watch examples of our video maker technology on the youTube blogHeard channel here:

http://www.youtube.com/user/blogHeard

We are a LAMP / S3 / OS / DSP house. We make extensive use of APIs to use external services such as googleCL and PayPal. For our automatic video conversions we transparently (to the user) use DSP (Digital Signal Processing) for text processing to mp3 audio and image processing to youTube format png images and then we render the audio and images to MP4 for youTube upload. We handle all the high bandwidth transfers, such as youTube uploads, for the users.
